answer: `->get()` returns a collection. You want to do `->first()` which will give you a single Wardrobe model. Then you should be able to call the `wardrobeimage()` method on that model.

answer: Take a look at [this answer](http://stackoverflow.com/a/3840771/243373) on StackOverflow on the question [Getting result of dynamic SQL into a variable for sql-server](http://stackoverflow.com/q/3840730/243373). After retrieving the result from the query, add this to your running total (`SET @T=@T+@R`).

How to validate an array of string with an enum in Mongoose?

I have an array of strings, that can only contain 6 kind of values. I've written this validation in my Mongoose schema:

skills: [
      { type: String, enum: ["marketing", "sales", "tech", "hr", "management", "finance"] },
    ]

When creating an user with the key skills: ["sales", "hr"], mongoose crashes, claiming that:

Error: UserDB validation failed: skills.0: ["sales", "hr"] is not a valid enum value for path skills.0.

How to fix this?
answer: How are you running the code? I suspect you are running it in the background and the shell is already accepting a new command; the script is simply writing output to your terminal until it exits.

answer: I would make `Channels` an `ObservableCollection`, to start with. If items are added or removed, I'd add/remove them instead of recreating the collection. In general, your second to last paragraph is on the money: Alter existing things which raise appropriate change notifications. Gets kinda tangled relative to just plopping in the whole new current state, but if you need to do that, you need to do that. P.S.: What rory.ap said.
